{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608725/1958030101/0001.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER FORECAST\nPartly cloudy today, tonight and tomorrow.\nLow 37 tonight. Little temperature change\ntomorrow. (Full report. Page A-2.)\nTemperatures Today\nMidnight 50 6am 43 10 am 47\n2am 49 Bam 45 11 am 48\n4 am\u201446 9 am\u201446 Noon 48\n106th Year. No. 60.\nDoctors Report\nFull Recovery\nOs Eisenhower\nPresident Leaves\nWalter Reed After\nReceiving Checkup\nBULLETIN\nPresident Eisenhower was\npronounced completely re\ncovered today from the\nstroke-like cerebral occlusion\nhe suffered last November 25.\nThe President, smiling and\ntelling newsmen he felt \u201cfine,\nfine,\u201d left Walter Reed Hos\npital at 12:20 pm. after\nundergoing a neurological\nexamination and a tooth ex\ntraction there.\nA team of three specialists\nin neurology gave this report\nthrough White House Press\nSecretary James C. Hagerty:\n\u201cThe President underwent\nthis morning at Walter Reed\nGeneral Hospital a thorough\nneurological examination in\ncluding an electro encephalo\ngram (brain-wave examina\ntion).\n\"The findings of these ex\naminations were completely\nnormal. There is no evidence\nof any damage to his central\nnervous system.\n\u201cThe President has com\npletely recovered from the\nminor speech disturbance\nwhich he suffered on Novem\nber 25, 1957.\u201d\nBy GARNETT D. HORNER\nStir staff Writer\nPresident Eisenhower, mak\ning a \u201cnormal\u201d recovery from\nthe extraction of a split molar\ntooth, was undergoing a neuro\nlogical examination at Walter\nReed Army Hospital today.\nThe examination by three\nneurology specialists was a de\nlayed checkup on the Presi\ndent\u2019s recovery from the stroke\nlike cerebral occlusion he\nsuffered last November 25.\nTo all appearances. Mr.\nEisenhower has recovered from\nthe effects of that illness. But\nhe had not received a medical\ndischarge pending the exam\nination today which came more\nthan a month later than origi\nnally planned.\nThe President had what was\ndescribed as a \u201cnormal and\nsuccessful\u201d extraction of an\nupper molar tooth in the Wal\nter Reed Dental Clinic yester\nday morning.\nMr. Eisenhower was described\nthis morning as \u201ccoming along\nfine\u201d as regards the extraction.\nHe planned to return to the\nWhite House about noon today.\nReads and Works\nHe spent most of the rest of\nyesterday in bed in the presi\ndential suite at the hospital,\npart of the time reading a pa\nperback Western novel ana later\ndoing some work on documents\ntaken to him by Press Secre\ntary James C. Hagerty.\nMr. Hagerty said part of\nthe reason for the President\u2019s\nstaying overnight in the hos\npital was \u201csome concern\u201d by\nhis doctors about the possi\nbility of excessive bleeding\nafter his tooth extraction.\nSince his September. 1955,\nheart attack. Mr. Eisenhower\nhas been taking anti-coagulant\ndrugs six days a week. These\ndrugs, reducing the chance of\na blood clot forming to cause\nanother coronary thrombosis,\ncarry a risk of increasing the\npossibility of hemorrhage.\nBut the President was taken\noff the anti-coagulants tempor\nrarily. His prothrombin rate,\nor blood clotting time, was\nfound satisfactory for the tooth\nextraction yesterday morning.\nAnd no excessive bleeding de\nveloped\nNormal Recovery\nSome five hours after the ex\ntraction. Mr. Hagerty gave\nnewsmen this report from the\nPresident\u2019s doctor and dentist:\n\u201cThe President\u2019s reaction to\nand recovery from the extrac\ntion are normal in every re\nspect.\u201d\nCol. Robert B. Shira, chief of\nSee EISENHOWER, Page A-3\nFOR YOUR\nDREAM HOUSE\nSHOP\nTHE STAR\nREAL ESTATE\nSECTION\nTODAY\nToday and every Saturday\nshop The Star for a wide\nvariety of best real estate\nofferings by leading build\ners and brokers throuhout\nthe Washington area.\nFor the home of your\ndreams, in the right loca\ntion, at a price you can\nafford to pay.\nBEFORE YOU IUY\nSHOE THE STAR FIRST\nPhone ST. 3-5000 WASHINGTON, D. C\u201e SATURDAY, MARCH 1, 1958\u201432 PAGES Home Delivered: E n V\u201c u \u00a3:v MonUl ftgg 5 CENTS\nw.iiprn.jyajL,.. --1. mu---I lift i. 1 10 l\nx-\nTHE THINGS THEY DO TO GET ALOFT!\nThe Army\u2019s revolutionary vertical take-off and landing flying research\nvehicle recently unveiled by Doak Aircraft, Torrance, Calif., combines\nfeatures of the helicopter and conventional aircraft. The ducted propel\nlers at the wing tips are rotated to vertical to take off like a \u2019copter.\nAloft, they are rotated forward for operation as a conventional plane.\nMaryland Income Tax\nIncrease Held Possible\n$33 Million New Revenue Needed\nAs Assembly Session Nears End\nBy CHARLES L. HOFFMAN\nStar Staff Writer\nANNAPOLIS, Mar. I.\u2014Raising some $33 million-plus in\nnew taxes is the new problem the Maryland'General Assem\nbly faces in the final four days of the 1958 session.\nAfter more than three.weeks of budget scrutiny, the\nHouse and Senate Finance Committees conceded last night\nthat they were able to cut only some $7 million off Gov. Mc-\nKeldin\u2019s proposed $184.7-mil\nllon budget. That is about one\nthird of the proposed increase\nin spending at the State level.\nIndications today are tbat\nthe Assembly probably will try\nto restrict their tax increases\nto one major category\u2014mainly\nthe Income tax.\nAt the same time General\nAssembly financial experts are\nexpected to press for removing\nsales tax exemptions on soaps\nand baby powders and the like\nand restaurant meals to raise\nsome $4 million in new revenue.\nMay Lower Minimum\nThey are also reportedly are\nleaning toward the lowering of\nthe sales tax minimum from 51\ncents to 35 cents. Some legis\nlators express an opinion that\nthis would raise an additional\n$3.5 million.\nBut the big increase would\nbe in the Income tax. By in\ncreasing the rate from 2 per\ncent to 3 per cent the State\nwould raise an additional $25.2\nmillion.\nThese are the major in\ncreases considered most likely\nby legislators in the financial\nfield here who decline to be\nidentified.\nAt the same time, there were\nreports that Senate Majority\nLeader Harry T. Phoebus\nmight try to impose additional\nlevies on beer and wine sales\nThe legislators\u2014and all this\nIs unofficial at this time\u2014re\nportedly lopped some $2.8 mil\nlion off the $3.3 million pro\nposed in the State employes\u2019\nsalary increases.\nNew Law Signed\nAnother $960,000 would be\nsaved by a law signed by Gov.\nMcKeldin yesterday requiring\nthat special fund agencies pay\ntheir costs of employes' retire\nment out of their special funds\ninstead of making raids on the\ngeneral fund.\nThe chief cuts made by the\nfiscal committees of the House\nand Senate reportedly were In\nhealthgand welfare fields.\nFor example some $436,000\nreportedly has been cut from\nmedical care expenditures. And\nanother $470,000, sources say,\nhas been slashed in proposed\nIncreases In food costs for the\nState\u2019s institutions.\nAssembly financial leaders re\nDealers Who Didn't Get\nAutos Sued by Tucker\nCHICAGO, Mar. I (JP).\u2014 The\nTucker Corp., which set out to\nmanufacture rear-engine autos\nin 1946, is suing four business\nmen who signed notes for deal\nerships that never came\nthrough.\nAn attorney for the company\nsaid it plans to sue hundreds\nof others who are in the same\nsituation.\nThe suits were filed yesterday\nin Circuit Court by Nathan\nYorke, trustee in bankruptcy\nfor the company.\nThe legal dilemma Involves\nbusinessmen who, seeking deal\nerships for the cars, paid a por\ntion of the fee in cash and\nsigned promissory notes for the\nrest. When the cars failed to\nmaterialize, they allowed the\npayments to lapse.\nAttorney Norman H. Nach\nman, representing Mr. Yorke.\nsaid the franchise agreements\nnever obligated Preston Tucker,\ncorporation president, to pro\nduce the autos, He said the\ntrustee now is attempting to\ncollect all possible assets of the\nbankrupt firm to pay creditors\nand United States Government\ntaxes.\n\u00aehe Itimitva ifef\nv J WITH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION Q-/\nportedly are ready to cut some\n$257,000 from the University of\nMaryland expenditures by In\ncreasing some university fees.\nThe legislators still may in\ncrease the cuts by another\nSBOO,OOO providing the two\nhouses and the Governor agree\non legislation that will re\nquire subdivisions to pay their\nshare of costs of collecting and\ndistributing to the subdivisions\nthe special taxes on alcoholic\nbeverages and the income taxes.\nDetails of the budget cuts\nwere expected to be announced\ntoday.\nAlternative Not Ready\nBut fiscal leaders reportedly\nare not ready to submit a tax\nprogram as an alternative to\nGov. McKeldin\u2019g proposals to\nincrease by 50 per cent the in\ncome and sales tax rates.\nPrivately, some fiscal experts\nin this Legislature expressed\nconcern over their ability to\npush through any increase in\nthe sales tax rates. They cited\nfor example a report that\nSenator Phoebus was opposed\nto any increases in the sales\ntax despite Gov. McKeldtn\u2019s\nrecommendations.\nSenator Phoebus, on the other\nhand, reportedly is ready to\npropose sharp increases In both\nthe beer and wine taxes.\nThe Senate and House fiscal\ncommittees last night met -for\nfour hours in an effort to\nreach agreement on budget\ncuts.\nThere were reports that the\nHouse committee which has\nbeen concentrating on the sl3\nmillion capital improvement\nprogram has cut as much as $5\nmillion from it.\nBoth the Senate and House\ncommittees were expected to\nname leading members to con\nfer this week end in an effort\nto reach agreement not only\non budget cuts but on new\ntax programs to meet the deficit\nthe State faces this year.\nQuake Shocks Lima\nLIMA, Peru, Mar. 1 (IP). \u2014A\nstrong and prolonged earth\nshock was felt in this capital\nand surrounding communities\nat 4:08 a.m. (EST) today,\nj There are no reports of prop-\nI erty damage or casualties.\n\u201cBy the wording of the fran\nchise agreement signed by the\ndefendants and hundreds of\nothers, who are to be sued in\nthe near future, the Tucker\nCorp. assumed no obligation\nfor the delivery of autos,\u201d Mr.\nNachman said.\n\u201cA study of agreements shows\nthat the purchasers paid merely\nfor the privilege of selling the\ncars. It and when they were\nmanufactured.\u201d\nThe four defendants are:\nAlexander V. Capraro, Chi\ncago, who paid SB,OOO in cash\nand signed an SB,OOO promis\nsory note for a franchise in Chi\ncago and four suburbs; Theo\ndore J. Taber. Yorkvllle, 111.,\nwho owes SII,OOO on the <4,000\npurchase price of a franchise;\nMario P. Otachettl, Santa Ana,\nCalif., who paid SB,OOO and\nsigned an SB,OOO note for ex\nclusive selling right in Santa\nAnna, and Lee Waldrip, Gaines\nville. Oa.. who paid $2,600 and\nsigned a $2,600 note for a\nGainesville franchise.\nMr. Nachman said collections\n:on the outstanding notes may\nyield <2.5 million to $3 million.\nA\nAF to Evaluate\nSolid Fuel Plan\nLiquid Propellant\nResearch Ordered\nBy L. EDGAR PRINA\nStir staff Writer\nThe Air Force has been or\ndered to begin research and\ndevelopment work to determine\nwhether a solid propellant\nintercontinental ballistic mis\nsile system is feasible.\nIn announcing this late yes\nterday, the Defense Depart\nment said the action was aimed\nat reducing \u201cthe complexity\nand increasing the reliability\nof long-range ballistic missiles.\u201d\nThe Ail Force currently has\ntwo liquid-fuel ICBM programs\nunder way\u2014the Atlas, which\nis expected to go Into opera\ntional production early In 1959,\nand the Titan, due a year or\nmore later.\nOther Orders\nWilliam M. Holaday, Penta\ngon guided missiles director,\nalso gave these orders to the\nAir Force:\n1. Accelerate research and\ndevelopment work on liquid\npropellants which would be\nmore easily handled and stored\nthan the tricky and volatile\nliquid oxgyen now in use.\n2. Consider use of the Navy\ndeveloped Polaris solid-fuel\nmissile as a second generation\nland-based IRBM \"in view of\nits early operational availa\nbility.\u201d\nDirective Formality\nThe directive on possible use\nof the Polaris by the Air Force\nis apparently a formality. The\nNavy has for months been\nturning over to the Air Force\nall its experimental data on\nPolaris which would be of use\nin adapting the weapon for\nland-based use. The Polaris Is\nexpected to be operational with\nthe fleet in 1960.\nThe Holaday directives re\nflect a growing frankness on\nthe part of defense officials\nthat the liquid long-range mis\nsiles now under development\nSee MISSILES, Page A-3\nTurk Ferry\nSinks, 184\nFeared Dead\nISTANBUL, Turkey, Mar. 1\nWP). \u2014A crowded ferry sank in\na sudden storm in the Sea\nof Mamora today. Istanbul ra\ndio said about 200 persons were\naboard and only 16 were res\ncued.\nThe ferry, the Uskudar, had\nleft Izmit shortly after noon\nfor a 50-mile voyage to Is\ntanbul.\nThe ferry was about a mile\noffshore and leaving the nar\nrow Oulf of Izmit when the\nstorm swept across the sea.\nThe ferry reportedly went\ndown so suddenly that most\npassengers were feared trapped\ninside.\nIstanbul radio said most of\nthe passengers were teen-age\nstudents. Izmit is located near\na United States base, but it\nwas not known whether any\nAmericans were aboard.\nFirst unofficial reports said\n300 were feared drowned. This\nwas based partly on an esti\nmate that 350 travelers had\nbought tickets in Izmit, one of\nTurkey\u2019s two main naval bases.\nSTOCKS\nIN THE SPOTLIGHT\nc *l\u00bbn\u00abe \u00b0L the *0 most active\nstocks lor the week:\nHljth. Low, Close. Che.\nLorlllard lfittl 4.TS 4o\u00bb. 42% 2V,\nStdOllllJ 1284 48}! 47\u00ab 4 B<?+\nOSSteel 1258 50% 58% SB% +l%\nRo\u00bb Dutch 1102 38% 37% 38%\nOetl Mot 1018 34% 34 34\nBentuet \u00bb03 1% 1 W\nBeth steel 787 ail\". 38V. 38\" I +\"1\nReetbeoii 717 23% 21\", 21%\nShell Trans 074 17}. 17V. 17%-*\nChrreier 850 51% so soft\u2014 l\nReeubStl (lift 42% 4IV. 42 tt\nSefewtv St H2o 28?! 27a! 2*\nNAmAvIA 583 28 26}, 27%+ 184\nRe\u00bbll Dr 558 12% 11% 12\nOil M Cl) 551 38% 37% 37V,\u20142V,\nAm Motor, 523 0 8% B% V,\nWeet Elec 513 62% 60V, B(>%-_l'4\nAm TAT 404 172*/, 172 172%+\nPenn-Te* 491 i% 3% S%\u2014\nOen Elec 480 41% 88% 60%\u2014%\nReds Reverse\nOK Pre-Summ\nAdministration\nMay Support\n8.5% Pay Raise\nCarlson Believes\nFigure Acceptable\nTo White House\nBy JOSEPH YOUNG\nStar Staff Writer\nThe possibility that the ad\nministration might go as high as\n8.5 per cent in supporting pay\nraises for Government classi\nfied employes was strengthened\ntoday, following the Senate\u2019s\naction last night in approving\nFederal pay-raise legislation.\nThe Senate approved only a\n7.5 per cent increase for\nPostage Boost Voted in Senate Faces\nFight. Page A-2\nclassified workers as compared\nto a 12.5 per cent raise for\npostal workers.\nBut Senator Carlson, Repub\nlican of Kansas, top minority\nmember of the Senate Civil\nService Committee and a good\nfriend of President Eisenhower,\npredicted an 8.5 per cent in\ncrease would be acceptable to\nthe White House.\nSenator Carlson yesterday\ntried unsuccessfully to trim the\n12.5 per cent postal employe\nraise to 8.5 per cent. He had\npredicted that such a compro\nmise increase would be ap\nproved by Mr. Eisenhower. But\nthe Senate rejected the 8.5 per\ncent postal raise proposal by a\nvote of 54 to 29.\nEquality Promised\nHowever, Senator Carlson,\nafter the Senate approved the\n7.5 per cent classified employe\npay raise measure, declared:\n\u201cI want to tell classified em\nployes that whatever we do for\npostal workers we will do for\nthem.\u201d\nThe Kansas Republican said\nhe would move in House-Senate\nconference to correct Inequities\nbetween the classified and\npostal employe pay raise bills\nThe 12.5 per cent postal em\nploye pay raise bill was ap\nproved as part of the postal\nrate increase measure. Since\nthe postal rate bill already has\nbeen approved by the House, it\nwill go directly to House-Senate\nconference. This will avoid the\nnecessity of having the House\nact on the postal pay bill, even\nthough the House Civil Service\nCommittee has approved a 15\nper cent postal pay raise\nmeasure.\nThe Senate then approved\nthe 7.5 per cent classified em\nploye pay raise bill as a sepa\nrate measure.\nJohnston Agrees\nChairman Johnston of the\nSenate Civil Service Commit\ntee attempted to attach the\nclassified pay bill as part of\nthe postal rate-postal pay bill,\nbut various Senators objected\nand Senator Johnston agreed\nContinued on Page A-3, Col. 1\nDies' Son Injured\nCritically in Crash\nGALVESTON, Tex., Mar. 1\n(IP).\u2014Martin Dies, jr., 36. son\nof the Texas member of Con\ngress, was reported in a very\ncritical condition today with a\nbroken neck, a skull fracture\nand a leg fracture suffered in\na car-truck crash.\nMr. Dies and a partner in his\nLufkin (Tex.) law firm were\ninjured last night in a collision\nwith a shrimp truck on Bolivar\nPeninsula, across the bay from\nGalveston.\nThe other man. Clark Ander\nson, 42, also was reported in\na critical condition.\nBeaver's Brain Studied\nFor Space Flight Tips\nBy the Associated Press\nThe Air Force is supporting a\nstudy of the beaver's brain in\nhopes it may lead to possible\nmeans for artificially increasing\nthe efficiency of space explorers.\nAn Air Force spokesman said\nthat if chemical or other con\ntrol means were found, it might\nbe possible to:\n1. Develop a kind of super\nefficient space navigator.\n2. Help fivers of combat air\nplanes \u201cto increase their fight\ning capabilities and abilities to\nwithstand jressure from the\nenemy, tfl\u00dfkhralnwashing.\u201d\nThe being studied\nbecause iMPes things by in\nstinct that seem to be highly\nintelligent, such as the build\ning of dams.\u201d the spokesman\nsaid.\nThe spokesman stressed that\ntttl Immediate objective of the\nresearch is to Increase basic\ninformation about the animal\nbreln\nIf findings in the study were\nK\nKorean Reds to Release\nAll on Seized Plane\nTOKYO, Mar. 1 (IP).\u2014Com\nmunist North Korea said to\nnight it is \u201cprepared to return\nat an appropriate time\u201d the\ntwo American pilots or a South\nKorean airliner that landed at\nPyongyang February 16.\nThe two Americans, plus two\nGerman citizens and any of\n\"That\u2019i Wonderful\" Cries Wifo of\nFreed Flyer. Fage A-7\nthe 30 South Koreans aboard\nthe plane who want to go home\nwill be allowed to leave, the\nCommunists said.\nThe announcement by Pyong\nyang radio did not specify when\nthey would be released.\nNegotiations Refused\nThe broadcast quoted a North\nKorean Foreign Office state\nment dated yesterday. It said\nthe decision was made \"in com\npliance with requests of the\nUnited States and* German\ngovernments\u201d sent through\nMoscow. The two governments\ndo nos recognize the North Ko\nrean regime and refuse to deal\ndirectly with it.\nThe Communists had said\nearlier they would release the 34\npersons on the DC-3 Airliner\nif the South Korean govern\nment would negotiate with\nPyongyang for them. South\nKorea continued its refusal to\ndeal with the Red regime.\nThe pilots are Willis P,\nHobbs of Vallejo, Calif., and Air\nForce Lt. Col. Howard W. Mc-\nClellan of Buchanan, Mich.\nThe Korean language broad\ncast heard in Tokyo said the\nAmericans and Germans will be\nturned over to official repre\nsentatives of the United States\nand German governments at\nPanmunjom \u201cor at any other\nplace mutually agreed upon\nwithin North Korea.\u201d\nAsk Red Cross Role\nThe South Korean passengers\nwill be turned over to South\nKorean Red Cross representa\ntives at Panmunjom \u201cor at any\nother place within North Ko\nrea mutually agreed upon,\u201d the\nbroadcast said.\nSouth Korean officials have\ncharged that the plane was\nseized by Red agents while fly\ning from Pusan to Seoul. The\nplane kept flying north when\nStabbed, Beaten, Nailed\nI n Box, Korean Boy Says\nSEOUL, Mar. 1 (IP).\u2014A Ko\nrean boy who was nailed Into a\nbox and flown 25 miles by Unit\ned States Army men charges\nhe was stabbed three times,\nbeaten and his hair cut and\ntarred, the Army said today.\nThe first report In the Army\u2019s\ncontinuing investigation of the\ncase said Kim Choon H, 14,\ncharged that Capt. Marvin E.\nKemp of Kilmichael, Miss., beat\nand stabbed him and an un\nidentified soldier also beat him.\nThe report made no comment\non the accusations. Gen. George\nDecker, United States com\nmander in Korea, said Wednes\nday he regretted the situation\nand promised \u201cappropriate ac\ntion.\u201d\nThe boy was pronounced In\nsatisfactory condition after an\nexamination Thursday at an\nArmy hospital. The Army said\nKim was caught early Tuesday\nwith stolen Items at the Bth\nArmy Aircraft Maintenance\nCenter at Ascom City.\nSays He Was Stabbed\nThe report said Kim charged\nthat Captain Kemp \u201chit him\nnumerous times and stabbed\nhim just below both knees and\nin the arm with the point of a\nknife He also said another\nfound applicable to man, he\nsaid, a search might then be\nmade to determine whether\ndurgs or phychological meth\nods, including hypnosis, might\nbe applied to man to \"improve\nthe behavior pattern.\u201d\nFor example, the spokesman\nsaVi. such things as these\nmight be envisioned if the re\nsearch worked out well:\nProviding military men with\na drug that would buttress a\ncertain brain area and make\nthem resistant to brainwashing\nPretreating space naviga\ntors to \"extend the time they\ncould stay awake and be effec\ntive\u201d Overcoming the in\nability to remember mathe\nmatical figures in an otherwise\ngood prospect for space flight.\nThe research is being done\nby Dr. George Pillerl of the\nBrain Research Institute, Uni\nversity of Berne, Switzerland\nDr. Pillerl came to this coun\ntry about a month ago to get\nbeaver brains for the research.\n.\u00a7Ei3f jS&L\njgS\nwe? jm umpnn\nCOL. HOWARD McCLELLAN\njm\n\nV:\n1 'P&gjMpfjK\nME\nWILLIS P. HOBBS\n\u2014AP Photos\nit reached Seoul and landed at\nPyongyang, the North Korean\ncapital.\nA North. Korean newsman\nsaid that some of the persons\naboard were receiving medical\nattention. This was interpreted\nas Indicating there had been a\nmidair battle for control of the\nplane.\nThe broadcast said the 34\npersons are \u201cbeing accorded\ngood, humanitarian treatment.\u201d\nIt repeated earlier contentions\nthat the 34 had defected to the\nnorth, rather than being forced\nto go into the Communist area.\nUnited States soldier mistreated\nhim by striking him.\u201d\n\u201cThe investigation disclosed\nthat Kim\u2019s hair was cut off by\na pair of electric hair-clippers\nand tar-like substance was\ndaubbed on his head,\u201d the re\nport continued.\nThen the boy was ordered\ninto a box used for transporting\nairplane parts. The Army said\nearlier it was 39>/ 2 by 16 *4 by\n15 inches. \u201cIt is alleged that\nM. Sergt. Robert E. Widensaul\nof Pottstown, Pa., nailed down\nthe lid,\u201d leaving some breath\ning holes.\nMoved by Helicopter\nAbout five hours later \u201cit is\nelleged MaJ. Thomas G. James I\nof Plymouth, Pa., had the box\nmoved to a helicopter\u201d and\nflew it to an Army airfield at\nUijongbu. He \u201cnotified the\nUijongbu airport by radio that\nhe had a box of spare parts\nand on landing it was taken\nto the supply room,\u201d the report\nsaid.\n\u201cThere a Katuso soldier\n(Korean training with the\narmy) heard whimperings from\nthe box and he and a United\nStates soldier opened it, dis\ncovering the boy.\u201d\n\"According to the investiga\ntion Maj. James entered the\nsupply room at this time and\nstated this was a \u2019slicky boy\u2019\nand that he was to be escorted\nfrom the airfield.\u201d\n\u201cKicky boy\u201d is slang for boys\nadept at thievery.\n2 Intruders Beat\nAnd Rob Woman\nA 27-year-old woman was\nbeaten on the face early today\nby two men who entered her\napartment and fled with S2O\nand some clothing.\nJoan Kimes of 2809 Fifteenth\nstreet N.W., the victim, may\nhave suffered a fractured Jaw.\nShe is in Episcopal Hospital.\nMiss Kimes told police she\nwas awakened by the two men\nin her bedroom about 6 a m.\nOne of them beat and choked\nher while the other ransacked j\nthe apartment, taking the i\nmoney, several sweaters and\nsome costume Jewelry, she said.\nShe described them as col\nored, one about 35, medium\nbuild, wearing dark khaki\nclothing; the other about 25,\n5 feet 6 inches tall, also dressed\nIn dark clothing,\na\nREAL ESTATE\nSECTION\na\nPages B-1 to B-12\nStand,\nt Talks\nOffer Short,\nHowever, of\nU. S. Terms\nBy EARL H. VOSS\nStar Staff Writer\nThe Soviet Union has pro\nposed a pre-summit meeting of\nas many as 27 foreign ministers\nin April.\nThe participants would pre\npare an agenda and name ths\nparticipants for a summit con\nference to be held later.\nThe Soviet reversal of its\nposition on a pre summit\nforeign ministers\u2019 meeting is\nunderstood to have been con\ntained in a note Soviet Foreign\nMinister Andrei Gromyko\nhanded to American Ambas\nsador Llewellyn Thompson in\nMoscow yesterday.\nThe White House gave fur\nther indication of Sovlet-\nAmerican activity to arrange\nhigh-level negotiations. Presi\ndent Eisenhower\u2019s Monday ap\npointment list included an un\nusual 11 am. meeting with\nSecretary of State Dulles and\nthe new Soviet Ambassador,\nMikhail Menshikov.\nMr. Eisenhower read the text\nof the note this morning at\nWalter Reed Hospital before\nreturning to the White House.\nPreviously, the Soviet Union\nhas objected to holding any\nkind of foreign ministers\u2019 con\nference before a summit meet\ning.\nFalls Short on Terms\nThe changed Soviet attitude,\nhowever, still does not meet\nPresident Eisenhower's previ\nously stated conditions for a\nmeeting with Soviet Premier\nBulganin and other government\nheads at the summit.\nIt is understood that Ameri\ncan officials do not believe that\nexploration of agenda items\nfor a summit conference would\nprovide the necessary assur\nances that significant agree\nment could be reached at the\nsummit as Mr. Eisenhower has\nstipulated.\nSoviet leaders have previously\nindicated they would be willing\nto have as many as 27 nations\nparticipate in a summit con\nference. These would include\nthe 15 NATO members, the\neight Warsaw pact nations and\nseveral neutrals, such as the\nnew United Arab Republic (for\nmerly Egypt and Syria), India,\nYugoslavia and Sweden.\nIt is reliably reported that\nthe Soviet note leaves open the\nquestion of what nations should\nparticipate in the April foreign\nministers\u2019 conference. Mr. Gro\nmyko is understood to have in\ndicated, however, that he is\nwilling to have all of those pre\nviously suggested for summit\nparticipation or fewer, depend\ning upon wishes of the West,\nFirst Word From Paris\nThe new Soviet attitude was\nconveyed to all Western gov\nernments yesterday. First news\nof the change came from Paris,\nwhere the French Foreign Office\nannounced the Soviet Union\nhad accepted a French pro\nposal for a foreign ministers*\nconference restricted to agree-\nSee CONFERENCE, Page A-X\nAirman Fatally Burned\nFighting Fire at Base\nOREENHAM COMMON. Eng\nland, Mar. 1 (IP).\u2014A United\nStates airman was fatally\nburned fighting a fire which\nstarted when a B-47 bomber\njettisoned its fuel tanks. They\nbounced out of the regular\nwaste area and caught fire.\nNine other airmen were\nburned, none seriously. The\nname of the dead eimum waa\nwithheld until his family could\nbe notified.\nThe tanks ricocheted out of\nthe drop area at this United\nStates uir base and splashed\nflaming fuel into another plane\non the ground and a nearby\nhangar, rhe B-47 landed safely\nat another base.\nCHURCH'S DOORS\nALWAYS OPEN\nUNLOCKED DOORS et oil timM\nare the policy ot Anacostia Meth\nodist Church. Day and night activi\nties For all its members in rocontly\nexpanded facilities are described an\nChurch Fage, A-8.\nTHE DEDICATION of a clumsy,\nex-soldier who became a man of\nGod has inspired many parsons 'n\nthe intervening decades. A sketch\nof Brother Lawrence, a Carmelite,\nappears an Page A-11.\nGuide for Readers\nAmusements B 8 Lost, Found A-3\nChurches A-8-11 Music A-5\nClassified A-14-19 Obituary A S\nComics 8-10-11 Real Estate 8-1\nCrossword I-11 Society Al 3\nI Editorial A t Sports A-12 13\nEdit\u2019l Articles A SiTV-Radio 1-10 II\nHove The Star Delivered to\nYour Home Daily and Sunday\nDial STerling 3-5000","height":"28452","width":"18449"}}
